Q2: Backup and Recovery Strategies to Mitigate Ransomware Threats

The Simple 3-2-1 Backup Rule
Number	Meaning	Why
3	Keep 3 copies of your data	If one fails, others save you
2	Store on 2 different storage types	Local drive + Cloud or External disk
1	Keep 1 copy offsite	Safe from fire, theft, or ransomware
3. Three Types of Backups
Type	What It Does	When to Use
Full Backup	Copies everything	Once a week
Incremental Backup	Copies only new/changed files	Daily
Continuous Backup	Copies as changes happen	For critical files
4. Recovery Process (4 Simple Steps)
text
Step 1: DETECT      → Identify infected files
Step 2: ISOLATE     → Disconnect infected system
Step 3: RESTORE     → Copy clean files from backup
Step 4: VERIFY      → Check if files work properly
5. Key Protection Strategies
Strategy	How It Works	Benefit
Immutable Backups	Backups cannot be deleted or changed	Ransomware can't destroy them
Air-Gapped Backups	Backup stored offline/disconnected	Completely safe from attack
Versioning	Keep multiple past versions	Restore from before infection
Separate Credentials	Different password for backups	Hackers can't access backups
6. Best Practices Summary
Practice	Why It Matters
Test restore monthly	Ensure backups actually work
Keep backups 30-90 days	Can go back to clean state
Monitor backup failures	Catch problems early
Encrypt backups	Protect data if stolen
Use separate accounts	Prevent ransomware from reaching backups
7. Recovery Time Objectives
Objective	Meaning	Typical Target
RPO (Recovery Point Objective)	How much data can you lose?	1 hour - 1 day
RTO (Recovery Time Objective)	How fast must you recover?	4 hours - 2 days
8. What NOT to Do
Mistake	Consequence
Only one backup copy	Complete data loss
Never testing restore	Backups may be corrupted
Same password for backups	Ransomware can delete backups
No offsite copy	Fire/theft destroys all data
9. Simple Checklist
text
□ Do I have 3 copies of important data?
□ Are backups on 2 different storage types?
□ Is 1 copy stored offsite?
□ Are backups locked (immutable)?
□ Did I test restore this month?
□ Are backup passwords different from main?
□ Do I keep versions for at least 30 days?
10. Bottom Line
If You Have...	You Can...
✅ Good backups	Restore in minutes/hours
✅ Tested backups	Be confident it works
✅ Immutable backups	Ransomproof your data
✅ Offsite backups	Survive any disaster
Golden Rule
"Backup is not enough. Tested Restore is what matters."
